---
description: MoonDB schema and API conventions for building backends
alwaysApply: true
---

moondb-conventions:

- MoonDB uses declarative JSON schemas. Describe WHAT you want, not HOW â€” never write SQL.
- Send the FULL schema on every PUT /v1/schema. MoonDB diffs against the current version and auto-migrates.
- Column types: string, text, int, float, bool, date, datetime, timestamp, json, enum, ref, uuid, file.
- Short-form syntax: "string required unique", "int default 0", "ref users required", "bool default true".
- IDs are UUID v4, auto-generated. Never define `id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`, `email` (on auth tables), `password_hash`, `email_verified`, `verification_token`, `reset_token`, or any column starting with `verification_` / `reset_` on auth tables.
- For auth tables set `auth_table: true` â€” this auto-creates `email` (string, required, unique) and `password_hash`, and enables /auth/* endpoints (signup, login, refresh, me, change/forgot/reset password).
- Access levels: "public", "authenticated", "owner", "admin". Default is "authenticated" for all operations.
- When any access rule is "owner", set `owner_field` to a ref column pointing to the auth table (e.g. "user_id"). MoonDB compares it with the user id from the JWT â€” users only see/edit their own rows. The server FORCES this field to JWT.sub on INSERT and ignores client-supplied values; on UPDATE the owner_field is silently stripped from non-admin bodies. For auth_table itself use `"owner_field": "id"` (user owns their own row).
- Refs are always to the `id` column. on_delete options: cascade, restrict (default), set_null. Ref columns are auto-indexed.
- Enum values must match [a-zA-Z0-9_-]. Adding values is non-destructive; removing them requires `confirm_destructive: true`.
- Destructive schema changes (drop column, change type, narrow enum, drop table) require `confirm_destructive: true`. Without it, PUT returns a preview of the migration plan instead of applying.
- Schema options (top level): `timestamps: true` (default), `soft_delete: false` (default).
- AI endpoints: declare under top-level `ai_endpoints` in the same schema PUT.
    { "tables": {...}, "ai_endpoints": { "summarize": { "model": "gemma", "prompt": "Summarize: {{text}}", "access": "auth" } } }
  Call via POST /ai/{name}. Each endpoint has its own access rule.
- Three credentials, three different scopes â€” never mix:
    mk_...  X-API-Key       Platform account (manage projects)
    sk_...  X-Admin-Key     Project management (schema, config, admin endpoints, admin-access tables)
    pk_...  X-Public-Key    Client-side data access (public-read tables only)
- Never expose admin_key (sk_) in client code. Store in .env as MOONDB_ADMIN_KEY. Public key (pk_) is safe for the browser.
- Every error response has a `suggestion` field â€” read it to self-correct. Don't guess the fix; the suggestion tells you the next call.
- Re-fetch GET /p/{id}/v1/llm-context after every schema change â€” it's the canonical agent reference (always in sync with reality). Use GET /p/{id}/v1/openapi.json if you want the OpenAPI 3.0.3 spec instead.
